        <trans-unit id="102" translate="yes" xml:space="preserve">
          <source>How to: Use Triggers to Style Selected Items in a ListView</source>
        </trans-unit>
        <trans-unit id="103" translate="yes" xml:space="preserve">
          <source>This example shows how to define <ph id="ph1">&lt;xref:System.Windows.Style.Triggers%2A&gt;</ph> for a <ph id="ph2">&lt;xref:System.Windows.Controls.ListViewItem&gt;</ph> control so that when a property value of a <ph id="ph3">&lt;xref:System.Windows.Controls.ListViewItem&gt;</ph> changes, the <ph id="ph4">&lt;xref:System.Windows.Style&gt;</ph> of the <ph id="ph5">&lt;xref:System.Windows.Controls.ListViewItem&gt;</ph> changes in response.</source>
        </trans-unit>
        <trans-unit id="104" translate="yes" xml:space="preserve">
          <source>Example</source>
        </trans-unit>
        <trans-unit id="105" translate="yes" xml:space="preserve">
          <source>If you want the <ph id="ph1">&lt;xref:System.Windows.Style&gt;</ph> of a <ph id="ph2">&lt;xref:System.Windows.Controls.ListViewItem&gt;</ph> to change in response to property changes, define <ph id="ph3">&lt;xref:System.Windows.Style.Triggers%2A&gt;</ph> for the <ph id="ph4">&lt;xref:System.Windows.Style&gt;</ph> change.</source>
        </trans-unit>
        <trans-unit id="106" translate="yes" xml:space="preserve">
          <source>The following example defines a <ph id="ph1">&lt;xref:System.Windows.Trigger&gt;</ph> that sets the <ph id="ph2">&lt;xref:System.Windows.Controls.Control.Foreground%2A&gt;</ph> property to <ph id="ph3">&lt;xref:System.Windows.Media.Brushes.Blue%2A&gt;</ph> and changes the <ph id="ph4">&lt;xref:System.Windows.FrameworkElement.Cursor%2A&gt;</ph> to display a <ph id="ph5">&lt;xref:System.Windows.Input.CursorType.Hand&gt;</ph> when the <ph id="ph6">&lt;xref:System.Windows.UIElement.IsMouseOver%2A&gt;</ph> property changes to <ph id="ph7">`true`</ph>.</source>
        </trans-unit>
        <trans-unit id="107" translate="yes" xml:space="preserve">
          <source>The following example defines a <ph id="ph1">&lt;xref:System.Windows.MultiTrigger&gt;</ph> that sets the <ph id="ph2">&lt;xref:System.Windows.Controls.Control.Foreground%2A&gt;</ph> property of a <ph id="ph3">&lt;xref:System.Windows.Controls.ListViewItem&gt;</ph> to <ph id="ph4">&lt;xref:System.Windows.Media.Brushes.Yellow%2A&gt;</ph> when the <ph id="ph5">&lt;xref:System.Windows.Controls.ListViewItem&gt;</ph> is the selected item and has keyboard focus.</source>
        </trans-unit>
